      "id": "72efc273d1b8e91d",
      "text": "Already Herder wrote in 1797 in the astonishingly modern poem *Das Ich* (The Ego): \"Wilt thou come to rest, flee o friend, / The worst enemy, the personality!\" He elaborates how man is in constant flux and the ego or personality is only a chimera. According to Luhmann, the form of the person symbolizes the unknownness of the future. (Cf. Luhmann 1997, p. 1019.) \"One can know persons – and yet cannot know how they will act. This peculiar integration of past and future in the semantic form of individual/person is institutionalized in the social concession of freedom. This, as can easily be seen, comes at the expense of social security.\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 1019) This is in nuce the problem of modern society. (Possible solutions would have to be considered in detail, e.g. copying patterns of individuality; see Pott 1995). "
